               <p>STEPHEN HART. I am out of business. On the 28th of August I was in <placeName id="t18300916-293-crimeloc1494">Wilson-street, Finsbury</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-293-crimeloc1494" type="placeName" value="Wilson-street, Finsbury"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-293-crimeloc1494" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-293-off1492 t18300916-293-crimeloc1494"></join>, between four and five o'clock in the afternoon; I felt my handkerchief drawing from my pocket; I turned, and saw the prisoner running away - I pursued; a constable stopped him, and<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183009160127"></xptr>took this handkerchief from him, which is mine; I did not see who took it from me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-293-person2419">
                  THOMAS 
                  SAUNDERS
               <interp inst="t18300916-293-person2419" type="surname" value="SAUNDERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-293-person2419" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-293-person2419" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was coming from Finsbury-square, and heard Stop thief! called I saw the prisoner running, and putting something under his coat - I pursued him; he ran up the City stone-yard - I ran up, and took him: I looked under his waistcoat, and found this handkerchief.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been some time out of employ; I saw this handkerchief down by the gentleman's heels - I put it into my bosom, and the gentleman turned and cried Stop thief! I ran, and was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300916-293-verdict1495" type="verdictDescription">
